==English==

===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|en|aboundant|abundaunt|habundaunt|habundant||obsolete}}

===Etymology===
First attested about 1380. From {{inh|en|enm|abundaunt}},<ref name=AHD>{{R:American Heritage Dictionary|edition=1971|page=6}}</ref> {{m|enm|habundaunt}},<ref name=WI3>{{R:MW3 1976|page=8}}</ref> {{m|enm|aboundant}}, from {{der|en|xno|abundant}}, from {{der|en|fro|abondant}}, from {{der|en|la|abundāns}}, present participle of {{m|la|abundo||to overflow, to abound}}. Compare {{m|en|abound}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/əˈbʌn.dn̩t/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/əˈbʌn.dn̩t/|/əˈbn̩.dn̩t/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-abundant.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Fully sufficient; found in [[copious]] supply; in great quantity; overflowing. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=10}}</ref>
#* [W]ith their magical words they [poets] bring forth to our eyesight the '''abundant''' images and beauties of creation. — ''Leigh Hunt, On the Realities of Imagination''
#: {{ant|en|rare|scarce}}
# Richly [[supplied]]; [[wealthy]]; possessing in great quantity. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* '''Abundant''' in goodness and truth. — ''Exodus, 34:6''
# {{lb|en|mathematics}} Being an [[abundant number]], i.e. less than the sum of all of its [[divisor]]s except itself. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{ant|en|deficient}}

